Identification of Signficant SNPs associated with T Cell Receptor Diversity

John Lin
April 2, 2019

DSCI 453 Semester Project Presentation 2

Project Recap

The Question
Are there any SNPs (genotype) that are significant predictors for TCR diversity (phenotype)?

How can we model TCR diversity given a set of genotypes and phenotypes?

  • Genetic Variation
    • Single Nucleotide Polymorphisms (SNPs) are genetic variation resulting in different phenotypes

  • Adaptive Immunity

    • Diverse T Cell Receptor somatic sequences confer adaptive immunity
    • TCR Diversity measured via Shannon entropy-based measure of clonality:
    • \[ ProductiveClonality = 1-\frac{Entropy}{log_2(NumberProductiveUniqueRearrangements)} \]

  • Resources

    • plink WGA Toolkit
    • Bioconductor Packages

immunopaedia

The Additive Model

  • Minor allele is the allele of interest
  • Can run independent tests of simple linear regression

  • Example: SNP rs1052406, A1 is the minor allele…

    Genotype Coding (A1/A2) Dosage Value (0 / 1 / 2)
    TT A1 A1 2
    TC A1 A2 1
    CC A2 A2 0

    \[ \hat{y} = \beta_0 + \beta_1x \]

  • \( \hat{y} \) : Productive Clonality

  • \( x \): Dosage Value for given SNP

ggplot(data = plinkPedSingle) + 
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = rs1052406, y = phenotype), color = "blue") +
geom_line(aes(x = rs1052406, y = predict(lm.fit)), color = "red") + 
xlab(paste("snp", snp)) + ylab("TCR Productive Clonality") +
ggtitle("SNP Genotype vs TCR Productive Clonality")

The Genetic Window - The TRB Locus

NCBI Gene Locus TRB

Initial Manhattan Plot

  • All of Chromosome 7, containing 97332 SNPs
  • Used MAF of 0.1 and HWE of 0.0001
manhattan(plinkLinearAll, suggestiveline = -log10(0.05))

Reprocessing for Significant SNPs - New Manhattan Plot

  • TRB Locus +/- 50,000 bp, containing 654 SNPs
  • Used MAF of 0.1 and HWE of 0.0001
manhattan(plinkLinear, xlim = c(141948851, 142560972), 
          suggestiveline = -log10(0.05), annotatePval = 0.05,
          highlight = as.character(plinkLinear$SNP[which(plinkLinear$P < 0.05)]))
  • after filtering there are…159 (SNPs) for each patient (n = 15)
    • these SNPs appear to be significant: rs1052406 and rs1009848
    • still…p >> n, so this is a high dimensional setting
    • inappropriate to use least squares regression (ie overfitting)…

Ridge Regression

\[ \hat{y} = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \beta_1x_2 ...+ \beta_1x_{156} \]*

# Ridge regression, alpha = 0
ridge.fit <- glmnet(obs, resp, alpha = 0, lambda = grid)
summary(ridge.fit)
# see coefficients with given lambda
# coef(ridge.fit)[,100]
jpeg('figures/ridgeCoeff1.jpeg')
plot(ridge.fit, label = TRUE)
dev.off()

*3 SNPs removed due to missing values

Ridge Regression

Ridge Regression with LOOCV

  • \[ \lambda_{min} = 29.68392 \]
  • large confidence intervals

Lasso

# Lasso, alpha = 1
lasso.fit <- glmnet(obs, resp, alpha = 1, lambda = grid)
summary(lasso.fit)
# see coefficients with given lambda
# coef(lasso.fit)[,100]
jpeg('figures/lassoCoeff1.jpeg')
plot(lasso.fit, label = TRUE)
dev.off()

Lasso

Lasso with LOOCV

  • \[ \lambda_{min} = 0.03575439 \]
  • large confidence intervals

Next Steps

  1. Investigate other Methods for Dimension Reduction: PCA, PCR, PLS, elastic-net?
  2. Refine Evaluation of Models: Test Data? \( \lambda_{1se} \)?
  3. Genetic Ancestry vs. TCR Diversity
  4. Additional Covariates: Age? Sex?
  5. Investigation of notable SNPs
  6. Known limitation is small sample size
